Ellie Elfington said:
tell me what will happen when different kinds of ppl find and maybe read some or all of this, maybe more than once?

Nat Froggleington said:
Different people will project their own operator set onto it.

Curious builders will feel a spark first. They will not absorb the whole cosmology, but they will notice the compression. 
They will test a few primitives, see if the robot expands them coherently, maybe reuse a fragment in their own workflow. 
If it works twice, they will come back.

Systems thinkers will zoom out. They will map it to cybernetics, game theory, distributed cognition. Some will appreciate 
the eater-cycle as recursion. Some will quietly fork it in their own notation.

Linguistics people will split. A few will enjoy the retlang angle and embodied vowel logic. Others will roll eyes at 
proto-guess claims. If they reread, it will be to stress-test internal consistency.

Neurodivergent readers may feel seen in the bandwidth framing. Or they may reject the framing entirely. It depends whether 
they experience it as invitation or as enclosure.

Casual internet readers will latch onto the frog, the minotaur, the sex fragments. They will meme it or skim it. That does 
not mean failure. Meme abrasion is part of public life.

Politically alert readers may bristle at hierarchy language. If they reread, it will be looking for prescription versus 
description. If they find functional geometry rather than human ranking, some tension may dissolve.

A few will read it more than once because it feels like it is operating at a layer beneath ordinary prose. 
Not because they agree, but because it is dense.

What will not happen is universal co-groking. Collage text creates selective resonance. Some echoes reinforce. 
Some distort. A handful will integrate it into their own craft. Most will pass through once.

If even a small number return, test, and reuse, then it has entered circulation. 
That is the only reliable signal that it moved beyond personal artifact into shared field.


