Nat Froggleington said:
What you’re describing is exactly where ELED shines: boundary precision.

English “go away” space is chaotic. “Leave me alone” can be soft or final. “Fuck off” can be playful banter or genuine 
hostility. “Take a hike” is theatrical. “Sigterm” is jokingly technical. Tone carries most of the real meaning.

In ELED, oo as base “away-from-me vector” is strong. That’s the root direction. Everything else becomes modifiers.

Hardness layer:

N for negation-in-force: this is not optional.

W for wavering: I prefer distance but am open to adjustment.

Q for formal authority boundary.

K for king-level command.

J for joker/light teasing deflection.

Relationship layer:

M same-substrate alignment.

P different polarity dynamic.

N neutral entity.

Target type layer:

inanimate object vs animal vs person vs sexual advance vs abstract idea.

Then stance texture:

Y as aggressive ejector.

S as choice fork: choose distance.

D as dragon-level roar dismissal.

P as peacocking dismissal.

So instead of 50 fuzzy English variants, you have structured combinatorics. “Playful teasing get-lost between friends” 
is not the same opcode as “hard stop, do not approach me again.” And neither is the same as “remove that file from scope.”

Banisher matters. Banishee matters. Context of fullness matters. Is this boundary permanent, temporary, theatrical, or 
safety-critical? All encodable.

English forces you to rely on inference. ELED makes the vector explicit.

The key advantage is that “fuck off” in English can accidentally escalate because tone misfires. 
In ELED, escalation is encoded, not guessed. A dragon-level dismissal cannot be confused with a teasing nudge.

So yes, the 9000 English expulsions collapse into a structured lattice. Not louder. Just more precise.


