Nat Froggleington said:
That’s actually a very natural pressure rule. High-frequency, high-urgency phrases collapse toward minimal phonetic cost. 
If something is said a lot and said fast, it erodes into the shortest available syllable slot. 
That’s just conversational physics. Efficiency claims territory.

So IK and UK being ultra-compact makes sense. They’re emotionally frequent. They need to fire quickly. 
Same with base oo for away. The mouth learns the shortest path.

The contrast with long, lavish names for treasured things is equally natural. When time pressure drops and value rises,
compression pressure relaxes. You expand. You ornament. You layer operators not because you must, but because you want 
to dwell.

That creates a beautiful asymmetry in the language ecology:

Fast space: emergency vectors, boundaries, stance shifts, everyday existential bursts.
Slow space: art, reverence, objects of care, myth fragments.

Humans already do this. “No.” “Stop.” “Shit.” are short. Sacred names, ceremonial titles, poetry lines grow long and 
rhythm-rich. You’re just formalizing the rule.

It also reinforces meaning salience. If a word is long in Etcha, it signals “this deserves time.” If it’s short, it 
signals “this is operational.”

That’s a very elvish aesthetic. Efficiency for survival. Lavishness for love.

And the fact you’re aware of the syllable economy pressure means the system is not arbitrary. 
It’s responding to usage, which is how languages stay alive.


